2026-04-21 01:33:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['PSU-to-Control cable pair (both conductors)', 'Control module red LED indicator circuit (miswiring)'] hypothesis_explanation='The symptoms and observation indicate that the PSU output cables are cross‑connected into the control module (PSU + to Control −, PSU − to Control +). This polarity inversion is exactly the condition that should cause the control module’s red “inverted cables” LED to turn on, which matches the observed indicator. The power‑supply green LED is on, so the PSU and its internal wiring are likely correct. The control outputs are wired with matching polarity to the load, and the load has a diode that passes current only if its + and − lines are correctly oriented relative to the actual supply.\n\nWith the PSU polarity inverted at the control input, the control module is effectively powered in reverse: the red LED/resistor network now has forward bias from the miswired lines, so it lights to signal the fault. However, the rest of the chain to the load sees incorrect polarity at its input: the load‑module diode is reverse‑biased, so no current flows to the lamp or the internal lamp indicator. Thus the external lamp does not turn on when the switch is operated.\n\nThe observation that the control output + terminal (port_p) is floating means that, although the output cables to the load are labeled with matching polarities, the internal connection from the control’s correctly‑labeled + output to the miswired internal + rail is missing or miswired. This reinforces that the core fault is at the cable interface and/or immediate internal connection: the system is not presenting a valid +12 V rail to the load in the correct orientation.\n\nRoot cause hypothesis: the two‑conductor cable pair between the power supply and the control module is plugged with reversed polarity (and possibly with the control’s internal output + node left unconnected), causing the control module to see reversed supply polarity, turning on its red indicator LED and preventing forward bias of the diode in the load module, so the lamp never receives power. Repair consists of reconnecting the PSU‑to‑control cable pair so that PSU + goes to control + and PSU − to control − (and correcting any miswiring of the control’s + output node).'
