2026-04-21 01:33:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal wiring at output/switch node', 'control module output (+) cable termination', 'control module PCB trace between switch and output (+) terminal'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules now have correct polarity and healthy components: PSU cables have been replaced, the load-module diode and both lamps show correct continuity and resistance, and there is ~12 V present on the load-module input terminals. In a simple series circuit with good continuity and a ~120 Ω lamp, 12 V across the lamp branch should draw about 0.1 A and light at least faintly, yet neither lamp glows and no voltage drop is seen anywhere along the path. This implies that, in actual operation, the lamp branch is not truly in series with the PSU return; instead, the 12 V reaching the load appears to be a phantom/through-leak from the control module, likely via the red indicator LED network or a miswired trace, so that the lamp sees no real current path.\n\nA plausible single fault is a misconnection inside the control module around the switch and output (+) node, such that the control output pair is inadvertently tied (via a high-resistance or indicator path) to the input pair, rather than being switched in series. This would place nearly full supply potential on the load input without providing a low-resistance return path for the lamps, explaining why the red LED remains on, full 12 V is measured "everywhere", but essentially no current flows through the lamps. The most likely physical locations are the PCB trace/jumper from the switch to the output (+) terminal, or the termination of the control output (+) cable itself, possibly shorted to the indicator network or left effectively open in series while still capacitively/through-resistor coupled.\n\nTherefore the remaining root cause is an internal wiring/PCB fault at the control module output/switch node (including the control output (+) cable termination). Repairing/reworking this wiring to restore a proper low-resistance series path from PSU + → switch → control output (+) → load diode → lamps → control output (−) → PSU − should restore normal lamp operation and extinguish the red LED under correct polarity.'
