2026-04-21 01:34:11 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module internal wiring of red LED indicator branch', 'Control module internal 0 V rail connection for red LED branch'] hypothesis_explanation='The latest measurements show the red “Inverted Cables” LED branch forming a standard forward‑biased LED+resistor chain between the control module’s 0 V and +12 V rails even when the PSU polarity is correct. Specifically, the LED has ~1.29 V across it (11.98 V anode, 10.68 V cathode), and the resistor drops the remaining ~10.7 V (0 V to 10.68 V). This means the indicator branch is permanently connected between the + and − rails in the normal polarity orientation, not cross‑connected between swapped input lines as designed.\n\nBecause the load module, series diode, lamps, and all cabling and switch path have now tested nominal, and 12 V is present right through to the load input and across the lamps, yet no current flows, the only remaining credible fault consistent with all symptoms is a miswired red‑LED indicator branch inside the control module. It is likely tied incorrectly into the rail network so that it both: (a) lights even with correct polarity, and (b) diverts nearly all current (through a low‑value resistor path) away from the load, leaving effectively no current for the lamps to illuminate.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a wiring/PCB error inside the control module related to the red LED indicator branch and its connection to the internal 0 V rail. Repairing/correcting this internal wiring so that the LED branch is only across the rails in the inverted‑polarity condition should restore normal lamp operation.'
